Zo heb ik Sunweb ook al acht maanden geleden erop gewezen dat het een kwestie van tijd is voordat zulke CO2-neutraal-claims onderuit zouden gaan. Nee.https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/sunweb-stopt-met-claim-op-co2-neutrale-vliegvakanties-eric-stam â€¦

Twee: het probleem is echt veel groter en breder dan mensen zich realiseren. Natuurlijk hadden weer heel veel mensen een vliegvakantie geboekt, want de booschap dat je goedkoop je vlucht kunt compenseren / neutraliseren wordt door heel veel partijen verkocht.pic.twitter.com/eurEOd9UB6

Het effect is grote onderschatting van de klimaatimpact van vliegen en overschatting van effect van CO2-compensatie. Consumenten blijven enorm vatbaar voor de suggestie dat ze echt heel verantwoord vliegen zolang ze maar compenseren.pic.twitter.com/Ug1lYlMMzq

Met andere woorden: de extreme mate van de misleiding wordt niet herkend. Babette Porcelijn liet bijvoorbeeld goed zien dat als je compensatie goed wilt doen, het echt veel duurder zou moeten worden.  Zien we nu al. Hoe KLM de nieuwe opties in CO2ZERO-menu gaat uitleggen, tja pic.twitter.com/7M5o9ILus7

Drie: bedrijven komen ook nog massaal weg met het compleet negeren van de niet-CO2-gebonden klimaatimpact van vliegen. De Europese Commissie gaat al uit van ten minste een factor 2.  KLM houdt vol dat er geen wetenschappelijke consensus is. pic.twitter.com/UhhLIWvbKU

Drie: de Nederlandse pers laat het tot nu toe ook afweten. De uitspraak CO2-neutraal / CO2ZERO vliegen ging via Bloomberg de wereld over.  In Nederland is er nog geen Ã©Ã©n journalist of zelfs maar stagiair geweest die bij KLM een reactie heeft opgehaald.pic.twitter.com/cPhsSjkjH2

KLM zelf leek de afgelopen twee weken vastbesloten om deze uitspraak zo geruisloos mogelijk te laten overwaaien met veel luchtige content en nul inhoudelijke reactie.  Met als egg-citing hoogtepunt natuurlijk de vrolijke content op de socials met Pasen. pic.twitter.com/2EQeduLFBk

Terwijl er echt wel wat vragen te stellen zijn. De Reclame Code Commissie heeft een uitspraak gedaan over meerdere uitingen, niet Ã©Ã©n ontspoorde slogan. De RCC zag duidelijk het structurele patroon van misleiding.  Eigenlijk moet KLM het hele CO2ZERO-programma rebranden.

Snappen journalisten de implicaties onvoldoende? Is een verhaal over weer een RCC-uitspraak niet spannend meer omdat lezers / kijkers het inmiddels wel weten?  Domme insteek: misleiding & desinformatie doen gewoon hun werk als je er niet mee afrekent. Afdronk: 'both sides'.

Het CO2ZERO-programma van KLM bestaat sinds 2008.  Ik hamer daarop, want 14 jaar lang maakte KLM dus reclame voor CO2-neutraal vliegen. Dat is een heel lange tijd waarin de Reclame Code Commissie *niet* ingreep (waarschijnlijk bij gebrek aan goed onderbouwde klachten).

Misschien ligt het ook wel gevoelig op sommige redacties in verband met contentdeals met KLM (?) of de discussie die sowieso gevoerd wordt over de wenselijkheid van een verbod op fossiele reclame. Willen mediabedrijven zulke grote bedrijven ook niet een beetje te vriend houden?

Media krijgen natuurlijk vaak (makkelijke) kritiek, maar toen bijvoorbeeld in 2019 Sunweb aankondigde alle pakketreizen CO2-neutraal te maken vond de NOS het een verhaal waard. Bikkelharde uitspraak RCC over CO2-neutraal-reclame KLM: niks, nada, noppes.pic.twitter.com/45HmXGbGeB

Ook politieke partijen zouden zich moeten zich verhouden tot de stevige uitspraken van de RCC over fossiele misleiding bij Shell, KLM etc, maar doen dat - op PvdD, GL en Bij1  na - eigenlijk nauwelijks.  Kersvers PvdA-leider Attje Kuiken: vliegen hoort erbij voor faire prijs.

2) The really strange this is that it's dated to around the time of Christ...  The House of Judah was late to the game... 2,000 years late.  America was already settled & claimed...   Several times over.

3) Oh yes! America was the gem of the ancient world.  Everyone came... Egyptians, Minoans, Phoenicians, Hebrews, Scythians, Romans, the Danes...  Is there any proof?  And the real mystery here is why weren't we told?!  And why has the Smithsonian spent 200 years covering this up?

4) Why did they all come for the last 5,000 years?  Quite simply... Copper.  The best in the world. Not as ore that exist in the strata of the ground, but an actual mountain made of the purest copper on the planet.  And this made the treacherous trip worthwhile for all comers.
5) Take a look at these maps as to where this mother load of copper is located...  The upper Peninsula of Michigan, on the Great lakes.pic.twitter.com/QughnOD83O

6) This is my attempt to aggregate many sources, and form one, plausible explanation to this forgotten chapter of our history.  The Bible, hieroglyphics, cuneiform, phonetics, anthropology, archeology, linguistics, genetics, geology, myth, etc.  Possible?  A quick refresher...

7) First...   We have the age-old argument with regards to the Bible, the first man, the creation story, etc...  vs.  Science, genetics, carbon dating, etc.  HARD to reconcile both. So, I will be coming from the scientific context, using the Bible for clues, verification, etc.

8) First things first...  The Middle East is a hell of a lot older than you thought.  GÃ¶bekli Tepe is twice as old as Egypt's 1st dynasty.  The City of Jericho had a tower that stood 7,000 years BEFORE Joshua blew his horns.  The Stone Age.pic.twitter.com/OpD6SApPNn

9) Things picked up when copper was used for the first time in prehistory.  Copper was the first major technological advancement that gave a tribe an advantage over another using stone weaponry.  It ushered in easier agriculture w/ the plough.  The oldest was in Jordanâ€”4,000 BCEpic.twitter.com/aYyM6untXX

10) The knowledge of this new material, and how to gather ore & purify it through smelting, traveled fast in the ancient world.  The land of Canaan sits right between two great ancient civilizations.  Egypt and Sumer... Copper built empires.  Mesopotamiaâ€”4000 BCE Egyptâ€”3500 BCEpic.twitter.com/tiNoIsqPO4

11) Interesting side note: If we cross check those dates with the (non-canonical) Book of Enoch, we can see that "In the days of Jared" the watchers came down to mount Hermon.  "Azazel (satan) taught them the secrets of warâ€”magic, metallurgy, and weaponry, and jewelry.  3,500 BCEpic.twitter.com/g3OwHxFytW

12) We know where the early copper mines were because of recent (and old) archaeological discoveries, and through the words of the earliest historians, in both hieroglyphics and cuneiform...  Mostly in the Sinai and the Red Sea side of Arabia...pic.twitter.com/J9Q0yEnRSf

13) I was really, really trying to keep this thread on the shorter side... As a kind of prequel.  Because I wanted to save my "King Solomon's Mines & Stone of Scone thread," But dammitâ€”It's all flippin' connected... All of it.  This is going to be a monster thread.  Fair warning.

14) Now that I made the decision to merge threads, I don't have to tip-toe around this next group of mysterious people that made all this possible...  Before Phoenicia was Phoenicia (of King Solomon's time 1,000 BCE), there were indeed a sea-going coastal people in modern Lebanonpic.twitter.com/d78OQlmZo3

15) Byblos is as old as Jericho...   Neolithic remains date it to 8,800 BCE. Eusebius said Byblos was the oldest city in the world, founded by Cronus himself!  And Byblos is on the coast.   RIGHT in the middle of all the ACTION.   Sea trade. Land trade... Since day 1.pic.twitter.com/wMXka4Zta5

16) Want to know what else made Byblos the historic center of our sea-going tales of old?  It had an even bigger advantage than copper.  The Cedars of Lebanon.  The best wood in the world for shipsâ€”Rot resistant, insect-proof (resin), fine grain, good smell, and workable.pic.twitter.com/RgjMc19j5m

17) Despite the shore-hugging trips of the early Canaanites, they most likely did NOT travel much beyond the Mediterranean & Black Sea.  It took the migration of another people to the same lands of Canaan that would bring the sea technology needed to make Canaan into Phoenicia.

18) Before they packed up and moved into the coastal area of Canaan, the greatest ancient sea-faring people came from Bahrainâ€”a small island in the Persian Gulf.  The DILMUN  They WERE the sea traders between the Indus Valley, the Mesopotamian, and the Egyptian cultures.pic.twitter.com/b9XPUzAObr

19) It's debatable which group of people invented the sail. The earliest depiction of a sail was found in Kuwaitâ€”the painted discs.  Whether is was the Ubaid culture or the Dilmun, one thing is for sure. The Dilmun mastered ocean-going vessels.  Not the reed boats of the Tigris.pic.twitter.com/XkXZP6vLtj

20) Sometime between 2,500 BCE and 2,000 BCE the greater part of the Dilmun tribe left Bahrain and made the same journey from Ur to Canaan as did Abraham.   Instead of continuing to Egypt, however, they stopped just south of Byblos...  And founded Tyre.  The birth of Phoenicia.pic.twitter.com/mVVXWdXX0X

21) "These people, who dwelt on the shores of the Erythraean Sea, migrated to the Mediterranean and settled in the parts which they now inhabit, began AT ONCE, they say, to adventure on LONG VOYAGES, freighting their vessels with the wares of Egypt and Assyria."  â€” Herodotus
22) In fact, Strabo also felt that the Phoenicians were originally from Tylos.  Tylos was the name used by the ancient Greeks to refer to Bahrain.  Strabo was a Classical greek historian.

23) Before we depart from Bahrain, I'd like to point your attention to the following photographs. Please make note.  These ancient mounds are found all over the Island of Bahrain.  This will come into play later in our story.pic.twitter.com/UrcNtDWgCl
24) Correction: Strabo was a Greek historian in classical ROMAN times... Herodotus was from the Classical Greek period.

25) Ok... Let's recap...  Canaanites were there since the beginning...   The Dilmun came in waves from Bahrain and founded Tyre on an older, smaller ruinâ€”right next door to Byblos and equally positioned to use those precious cedars.  Then comes Abraham from Ur... Interesting mix.

26) Talk about MIXES!  For a Biblical perspective, it appears the cross section for all the Sons of Noah overlap the area in question.  Right smack in the middle... The (later) promised land.pic.twitter.com/xUqu0S47FW

27) The ebb and flow of kings, kingdoms, and peoples in the middle East is staggering. And because writingâ€”in all its formsâ€”was still primitive, we only have glimpses of these great migrations from the records of these kings.

28) If there ever was an ancient "melting pot" it occurred in two placesâ€”both Dilmun:  - Bahrain Dilmun: (Micronesia, Indus/Harappa, Mesopotamia, Ethiopia, Arabia, Egypt)  - Canaanite/Dilmun: (Canaan, Hittites, Assyria, Black Sea Tribes, Mittani, Minoans, Egypt, Libya)

29) It stands to reason that a sea people such as the Dilmun would need to learn communication skills quickly, if they were to be successful in trade and commerce.  Phonetics is a branch of linguistics based on the sounds of human speech, born in Phoeniciaâ€”in later years later.

30) Let's set the stage for a part of the story where we may introduce the FIRST lost tribes of Israel. 1,200 years before Nebuchadnezzar II the "destroyer of nations" sent the Israel's tribes far to the North, before coming back for (predominantly) the tribe of Judah in 587 BCE.
